            "content": "# Personal Photography Landing Page\n\n## Context\n\nThe user wants a personal landing page for their photography: a single `index.html` file with all CSS inline (in a `<style>` block — no external stylesheets, no JS frameworks, no build step). The workspace is empty except for a stub README, so this is a fresh, standalone file they can open directly in a browser or drop onto any static host.\n\n## Assumptions\n\n- No name/branding was given — use a placeholder name (\"{{userName}}\", derivable from the user's email) and placeholder tagline, clearly easy to swap.\n- Gallery images: use `https://picsum.photos` placeholder photos so the page looks real on first open; each `<img>` gets a comment noting where to swap in real photos. (Falls back gracefully to styled boxes if offline.)\n- No JavaScript needed — pure HTML/CSS.\n\n## File to create\n\n`index.html` (single file, ~250–350 lines) containing:\n\n1. **`<head>`** — meta viewport, title, and one `<style>` block with all CSS:\n   - Dark, gallery-like theme (near-black background, light text) so photos are the focus\n   - System font stack (no webfont dependency), generous letter-spacing for headings\n   - Responsive throughout via CSS grid + `clamp()` for type sizes\n2. **Hero** — full-viewport section: photographer name, one-line tagline (e.g. \"Landscape & street photography\"), subtle scroll cue\n3. **Gallery** — responsive CSS grid (3 columns → 2 → 1 on narrow screens) of 6–9 photos with hover zoom/caption effect, `loading=\"lazy\"`\n4. **About** — short bio paragraph with a small portrait placeholder\n5. **Contact / footer** — email link, placeholder social links (Instagram etc.), copyright line\n\nAccessibility basics: semantic sections, alt text on images, sufficient contrast, focus-visible styles on links.\n\n## Verification\n\n- Open the file in a browser: `open index.html`\n- Check: hero fills the viewport, gallery grid reflows at narrow widths (resize window), hover effects work, all links/anchors scroll correctly\n- Confirm the page still renders sensibly with images unloaded (offline case)\n"
